related_items.title: Collected poems of Edwin James Barclay.
partof: rare book and special collections division
description: "Monrovia." Typescript (Carbon copy). Pages [33-54] appear to be blank, except p. [37], which repeats first line of p. 16 [i.e. 17]; other pages have faint reverse image of a text. Accompanying material: calling card of James Robert Spurgeon, United States Secretary of Legation, Monrovia, Liberia. Poems on a variety of subjects; titles include Monrovia, Song of the Dead, biographical research disclosed no information about this writer.  Internal evidence suggests, however, that Barclay was probably African American or Americo-Liberian. 32 p. ; 20 cm.

related_items.title: The slumbers of the dead /
partof: rare book and special collections division
description: "Monrovia, Liberia, Africa." Typescript (Carbon copy). Pages 23-[24] (p. 24 is misnumbered 23) are bound after p. [26]. The word "denizen" has been corrected in pencil to "alien" on p. 5. A poem about life and the after-life, written in Monrovia, Liberia.  American Memory biographical research disclosed no information about this writer.  Internal evidence suggests, however, that Barclay was prpbably African American or Americo-Liberian. 24, [1] [i.e. 26] p. ; 20 cm.

related_items.title: Message of the President of the Republic of Liberia to the two houses of the legislature at the commencement of the session of 1868.
partof: rare book and special collections division
description: Text signed on p. 22: James S. Payne. LC copy has inscription in pencil on cover: Jas. S. Payne. DLC A report on the state of Liberia in 1868.  Among problems discussed are the country's debt, the need to expand and assimilate neighboring Africans, and the need for an appeal to African Americans for money to finance the colony. 22 p. ; 20 cm.
